(- casual one-off mentions stop polluting the top context window) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Examples:) Tj
T*
(- My name is Ravit should stay hot) Tj
T*
(- I had pasta on Tuesday should eventually cool down) Tj
T*
(- I love dark mode may stay warm or hot if repeated often) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Sentiment memory) Tj
T*
(This is the meaning behind facts layer.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Real-world problem:) Tj
T*
(- agents often store objective facts but miss subjective intensity) Tj
T*
(- user mentioned React is not the same as user absolutely hates React) Tj
T*
(- without sentiment memory, recommendations and personalization are shallow) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(What sentiment memory does:) Tj
T*
(- detects positive and negative opinion) Tj
T*
(- measures intensity) Tj
T*
(- stores evolving opinions over time) Tj
T*
(- preserves strong sentiments as high-salience memory) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Why this matters in practice:) Tj
T*
(- recommendations become better) Tj
T*
(- the agent can respond in a more aligned way) Tj
T*
(- it can detect preference shifts over time) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Example:) Tj
T*
(- I used to hate React, now I kind of like it) Tj
T*
(The system can track that evolution instead of treating both as the same flat fact.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(This is especially important for:) Tj
T*
(- personal assistants) Tj
T*
(- shopping and recommendation agents) Tj
T*
(- coding copilots adapting to user preferences) Tj
T*
(- long-term companion agents) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Poisoning defense) Tj
T*
(This is the memory security layer.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Real-world problem:) Tj
T*
(- an agent can be tricked into storing false or adversarial facts) Tj
T*
(- attackers can try to overwrite identity, instructions, user preferences, location, or) Tj
T*
(trusted memory) Tj
T*
(- even benign conversation drift can gradually corrupt memory) Tj
ET
endstream
